Visual Comparison

Original vs. New Local Shed assignment

  • The first shed shows initial pits which are removed in the first step of pit removal. This dem doesn’t exist in the original program.
  • The next two are the local sheds (shedno) after amalgamating the small ones
  • Sheds are identical except that in original, missing values get a shed of 0 whereas they’re marked as NA in LITAP

Original vs. New Fill Shed assignment

  • These are the fill sheds, which reflect how sheds combined during the third pit removal process
  • Shapes should be identical to pond filling, just the numbers may be different
  • Sheds are identical except that in original, missing values get a shed of 0 whereas they’re marked as NA in LITAP

New Pond data

Differences

pond <- arrange(pond, ShedNo)
orig_pond <- arrange(orig_pond, ShedNo)
c <- compare(pond, orig_pond)
## Pit Vol not the same, but within 3
## Pit area not the same, but within 5 cells
## Not all DrainsTo the same
## Not all NextPit the same
## Not all Becomes the same
## Not all InRec the same
## Not all OutRec the same
  • Most important values (pit area, pit vol, varatio) are identical, or only different by a small degree
  • Nextpit is often incorrect (not sure why)

  • Exact location of pourpoint between two watersheds is sometimes off by a cell or two (out rec and in rec)

  • DrainsTo off in one case, almost certainly due to tie breaking (going west instead of south)

pond[c$DrainsTo, ] %>% select(ShedNo, PitRec, PourElev, DrainsTo, OutElev, Becomes)
## # A tibble: 1 x 6
##   ShedNo PitRec PourElev DrainsTo OutElev Becomes
##    <dbl>  <int>    <dbl>    <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1     16   1321      100       11     100       0
orig_pond[c$DrainsTo, ] %>% select(ShedNo, PitRec, PourElev, DrainsTo, OutElev, 
    Becomes)
## # A tibble: 1 x 6
##   ShedNo PitRec PourElev DrainsTo OutElev Becomes
##    <int>  <int>    <dbl>    <int>   <dbl>   <int>
## 1     16   1321      100       13     100       0
  • Two becomes are switched, also due to tie breaking in order of filling?
pond[c$Becomes, ] %>% select(ShedNo, PitRec, PourElev, DrainsTo, OutElev, Becomes)
## # A tibble: 2 x 6
##   ShedNo PitRec PourElev DrainsTo OutElev Becomes
##    <dbl>  <int>    <dbl>    <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1      4  10921      100       12 99.9384      18
## 2      5  10961      100        2 99.9384      19
orig_pond[c$Becomes, ] %>% select(ShedNo, PitRec, PourElev, DrainsTo, OutElev, 
    Becomes)
## # A tibble: 2 x 6
##   ShedNo PitRec PourElev DrainsTo OutElev Becomes
##    <int>  <int>    <dbl>    <int>   <dbl>   <int>
## 1      4  10921      100       12 99.9384      19
## 2      5  10961      100        2 99.9384      18
  • But in the end, all become 19 anyway, does it matter?
